Abstract:\
Symmetric (e.g. prismatic or axisymmetric) domains are common in practical problems in acoustics, electromagnetism, fluid mechanics, etc. and often allow for a simplified treatment of an originally three-dimensional problem in a reduced two-dimensional domain. This is usually achieved by a Fourier series expansion in the symmetry coordinate which leads to a new equation for each harmonic that can be solved numerically by the finite element method [1,2]. For the formulation of magnetostatics via the curl-curl equation it is possible to eliminate one component of the vector potential by a gauge transformation for all except the zeroth harmonic. This leads to a fully two-dimensional problem for two-component vectors [3] that is efficiently solved via Nedelec edge elements. In this talk, the general derivation of the method as well as its application in magnetic confinement fusion devices [4] and other cases will be demonstrated.\
\
